1
00:00:02,166 --> 00:00:05,750
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 45429.3.</i>

2
00:00:05,750 --> 00:00:08,166
<i>While on a mapping survey,</i>
<i>we are conveying</i>

3
00:00:08,166 --> 00:00:11,041
<i>a delegation of</i>
<i>Ullians to Kaldra IV.</i>

4
00:00:11,041 --> 00:00:14,583
<i>These telepathic historians</i>
<i>conduct their research</i>

5
00:00:14,583 --> 00:00:17,792
<i>by retrieving</i>
<i>long-forgotten memories.</i>

6
00:00:19,500 --> 00:00:26,000
It's a chipped cup, off-white...
with a crack in it.

7
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:28,834
I can see it, but I don't
remember anything else about it.

8
00:00:28,834 --> 00:00:33,041
MAN: When you see it,
do you hear any sounds?

9
00:00:34,709 --> 00:00:37,000
No, I don't think so.

10
00:00:39,166 --> 00:00:41,458
Wait.

11
00:00:41,458 --> 00:00:45,375
Yes, uh... humming.

12
00:00:46,667 --> 00:00:48,000
Someone's humming.

13
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,417
A woman.

14
00:00:49,417 --> 00:00:52,083
Yes, but I don't
know who it is.

15
00:00:53,583 --> 00:00:55,709
Try to touch the cup.

16
00:01:01,208 --> 00:01:05,792
Ooh, it-- it has a sharp
edge where it's chipped.

17
00:01:05,792 --> 00:01:08,542
Is there anything
inside the cup?

18
00:01:16,291 --> 00:01:19,458
A liquid... dark.

19
00:01:19,458 --> 00:01:21,166
MAN:
Like tea?

20
00:01:24,125 --> 00:01:26,458
It's not hot.

21
00:01:27,834 --> 00:01:29,750
It's bitter.

22
00:01:29,750 --> 00:01:32,542
There's something else
inside the cup.

23
00:01:33,500 --> 00:01:36,625
Yes, a... a wooden handle.

24
00:01:36,625 --> 00:01:37,792
MAN:
A spoon?

25
00:01:37,792 --> 00:01:39,959
No, it's more delicate
than that.

26
00:01:41,166 --> 00:01:43,000
MAN:
Reach out for it.

27
00:01:48,667 --> 00:01:50,625
A brush.

28
00:01:51,917 --> 00:01:53,625
An ink brush.

29
00:01:53,625 --> 00:01:56,291
(<i> humming</i> )

30
00:01:59,125 --> 00:02:01,333
I hear that humming again.

31
00:02:01,333 --> 00:02:07,000
Keep listening to it,
and hold out the brush.

32
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,667
See if anyone
takes it from you.

33
00:02:10,667 --> 00:02:13,166
(<i> woman humming</i> )

34
00:02:13,166 --> 00:02:15,875
(<i> woman speaking in</i>
<i>foreign language)</i>

35
00:02:15,875 --> 00:02:19,041
It's Obachan...

36
00:02:19,041 --> 00:02:21,875
my grandmother.

37
00:02:21,875 --> 00:02:24,458
She's doing
ink brush writing.

38
00:02:25,583 --> 00:02:27,125
I can remember it now.

39
00:02:27,125 --> 00:02:30,417
She, uh... she used that cup
for cleaning the brushes

40
00:02:30,417 --> 00:02:32,375
and it was my job to
fill the cup with water

41
00:02:32,375 --> 00:02:34,333
and bring it
to the table.

42
00:02:34,333 --> 00:02:36,375
I would sit beside
her and watch

43
00:02:36,375 --> 00:02:39,709
the most beautiful
characters come from that brush

44
00:02:39,709 --> 00:02:43,250
and the whole time, she'd be
humming to herself.

45
00:02:43,250 --> 00:02:45,792
I-- I remember it
like it was yesterday.

46
00:02:45,792 --> 00:02:47,417
That is remarkable.

47
00:02:47,417 --> 00:02:49,834
You remembered
such vivid details.

48
00:02:49,834 --> 00:02:53,083
For years, I've seen that
old cup in my memory,

49
00:02:53,083 --> 00:02:55,041
but I could never
remember what it was

50
00:02:55,041 --> 00:02:57,792
or why it was important.
Thank you.

51
00:02:57,792 --> 00:03:00,291
Well, you're entirely welcome,
young lady.

52
00:03:00,291 --> 00:03:02,709
Perhaps someone else
would care to try?

53
00:03:02,709 --> 00:03:04,125
You, madam?

54
00:03:04,125 --> 00:03:07,834
You're thinking about that
first childhood kiss.

55
00:03:07,834 --> 00:03:10,417
Would you like to
remember more about it?

56
00:03:10,417 --> 00:03:12,583
Father, you know you're
not supposed to probe

57
00:03:12,583 --> 00:03:14,875
someone's memory unless
they've given you permission.

58
00:03:14,875 --> 00:03:17,291
You are right.

59
00:03:17,291 --> 00:03:21,125
But sometimes,
with a beautiful woman,

60
00:03:21,125 --> 00:03:24,083
I cannot help myself.

61
00:03:24,083 --> 00:03:27,083
(<i> laughing</i> )

62
00:03:27,083 --> 00:03:28,709
How about you, Commander?
Got any memories

63
00:03:28,709 --> 00:03:30,166
you feel like digging up?

64
00:03:30,166 --> 00:03:31,875
None that I'd care to
share with an audience.

65
00:03:31,875 --> 00:03:34,250
It's getting late.
I'd better be going.

66
00:04:12,959 --> 00:04:17,417
<i>Space, the final frontier.</i>

67
00:04:17,417 --> 00:04:21,166
<i>These are the voyages</i>
<i>of the Starship</i> Enterprise.

68
00:04:21,166 --> 00:04:23,083
<i>Its continuing mission--</i>

69
00:04:23,083 --> 00:04:26,917
<i>to explore</i>
<i>strange new worlds,</i>

70
00:04:26,917 --> 00:04:31,625
<i>to seek out new life</i>
<i>and new civilizations,</i>

71
00:04:31,625 --> 00:04:35,750
<i>to boldly go</i>
<i>where no one has gone before.</i>

72
00:05:38,917 --> 00:05:40,333
It is perplexing to me

73
00:05:40,333 --> 00:05:42,375
that the Ullians' ability
to retrieve memory

74
00:05:42,375 --> 00:05:44,375
is so highly prized.

75
00:05:44,375 --> 00:05:47,333
If an event were important
enough to be recovered,

76
00:05:47,333 --> 00:05:49,000
why would it
have been forgotten?

77
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,291
Well, it's not quite the same
for us as it is for you, Data.

78
00:05:52,291 --> 00:05:55,709
You record every second of
every moment of your life.

79
00:05:55,709 --> 00:05:56,834
That is correct.

80
00:05:56,834 --> 00:05:58,208
And then, if you
want to recall

81
00:05:58,208 --> 00:05:59,625
any one of those moments,

82
00:05:59,625 --> 00:06:02,291
you just access the
proper memory circuit.

83
00:06:02,291 --> 00:06:03,917
My understanding of
the human brain

84
00:06:03,917 --> 00:06:06,542
suggests the process
is the same for you.

85
00:06:06,542 --> 00:06:09,542
Each memory is encoded
in chains of molecules.

86
00:06:09,542 --> 00:06:11,000
If you want to
retrieve it,

87
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,583
you simply access the
proper RNA sequence.

88
00:06:13,583 --> 00:06:15,750
Yeah, that's true.

89
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:17,917
Then in what way
is it different?

90
00:06:17,917 --> 00:06:19,417
Sometimes
there are memories

91
00:06:19,417 --> 00:06:21,542
we just can't...
(<i> snaps</i> )

92
00:06:21,542 --> 00:06:23,875
...access at the
spur of the moment.

93
00:06:23,875 --> 00:06:26,250
For instance,
I have no recollection

94
00:06:26,250 --> 00:06:28,125
of how I spent my
last birthday.

95
00:06:28,125 --> 00:06:29,792
Birthdays are
important occasions,

96
00:06:29,792 --> 00:06:31,959
and you would think that I'd
remember how I spent the day,

97
00:06:31,959 --> 00:06:35,959
but right now, I can't even
remember... where I was.

98
00:06:37,417 --> 00:06:39,000
Deck two.

99
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:40,917
On the other hand,
I remember everything

100
00:06:40,917 --> 00:06:43,291
about the time I got my
first pet-- a Circassian cat.

101
00:06:43,291 --> 00:06:44,667
I was eight.

102
00:06:44,667 --> 00:06:46,917
I remember how
funny-looking he was.

103
00:06:46,917 --> 00:06:48,959
I remember how
excited I was.

104
00:06:48,959 --> 00:06:51,041
It was as if it
happened yesterday.

105
00:06:51,041 --> 00:06:52,959
Perhaps you remember the
pleasant memories

106
00:06:52,959 --> 00:06:54,750
and forget the
unpleasant ones.

107
00:06:54,750 --> 00:06:58,125
No, sometimes the bad memories
can be the most intense of all.

108
00:06:58,125 --> 00:07:00,041
It would seem there is
no predictable pattern

109
00:07:00,041 --> 00:07:02,417
to human memory.

110
00:07:02,417 --> 00:07:04,542
It would seem.

111
00:07:09,083 --> 00:07:12,000
This library of ours has been in
the planning stages for years--

112
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:13,959
a collection of the
retrieved memories

113
00:07:13,959 --> 00:07:15,959
of races from many
different star systems--

114
00:07:15,959 --> 00:07:18,917
What my son means to say
is we think of ourselves

115
00:07:18,917 --> 00:07:21,291
as archaeologists
of the mind.

116
00:07:21,291 --> 00:07:24,250
We believe that the history
of a world is contained

117
00:07:24,250 --> 00:07:26,375
in the personal
experience of its people.

118
00:07:26,375 --> 00:07:28,792
Rather like the ancient
oral historians on Earth.

119
00:07:28,792 --> 00:07:30,250
Exactly.

120
00:07:30,250 --> 00:07:33,500
The library we propose
will be a vast storehouse

121
00:07:33,500 --> 00:07:35,750
of these individual memories.

122
00:07:35,750 --> 00:07:37,750
That sounds like
quite a project.

123
00:07:37,750 --> 00:07:40,291
How long will it take to
finish your studies on Kaldra?

124
00:07:40,291 --> 00:07:41,709
Many months.

125
00:07:41,709 --> 00:07:43,291
We've been working
for years,

126
00:07:43,291 --> 00:07:46,417
and we've surveyed
only 11 planets

127
00:07:46,417 --> 00:07:48,709
in eight star systems.

128
00:07:48,709 --> 00:07:50,625
But it's our
way of life.

129
00:07:50,625 --> 00:07:52,291
We wouldn't want to
do anything else.

130
00:07:52,291 --> 00:07:55,125
Captain, Mr. Tarmin
gave us a demonstration

131
00:07:55,125 --> 00:07:56,792
of his abilities
this afternoon.

132
00:07:56,792 --> 00:07:58,500
It's fascinating.

133
00:07:58,500 --> 00:08:01,083
Perhaps you would like
to resurrect some memories?

134
00:08:01,083 --> 00:08:03,750
TARMIN: I'd be happy to probe
your recollections, Captain.

135
00:08:03,750 --> 00:08:07,250
Most people find it
an enjoyable experience.

136
00:08:07,250 --> 00:08:08,583
I'm sure.

137
00:08:08,583 --> 00:08:10,709
However, I don't think
I would make

138
00:08:10,709 --> 00:08:12,750
a particularly good subject.

139
00:08:12,750 --> 00:08:14,250
I'm sure you'd be ideal,

140
00:08:14,250 --> 00:08:18,000
and you must have
some intriguing memories.

141
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,500
TARMIN: We won't be on
your ship for long.

142
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:22,291
This may be your last chance.

143
00:08:22,291 --> 00:08:25,417
(<i> chuckling</i> )
Yes, well...

144
00:08:25,417 --> 00:08:29,208
Tarmin, we mustn't
influence people.

145
00:08:29,208 --> 00:08:31,875
We must let them
come to us willingly.

146
00:08:31,875 --> 00:08:34,250
I have found over the years

147
00:08:34,250 --> 00:08:36,291
there are many
who want the experience

148
00:08:36,291 --> 00:08:37,792
of memory retrieval,

149
00:08:37,792 --> 00:08:39,333
but who lack some
encouragement

150
00:08:39,333 --> 00:08:40,709
in order
to come forward.

151
00:08:40,709 --> 00:08:42,333
You, Mr. Worf.

152
00:08:42,333 --> 00:08:46,667
I would love to explore
Klingon memories.

153
00:08:46,667 --> 00:08:51,375
Klingons do not allow
themselves to be probed.

154
00:08:51,375 --> 00:08:53,625
But there is nothing to fear.

155
00:08:53,625 --> 00:08:56,000
Father...

156
00:08:58,250 --> 00:09:00,583
I am not fearful.

157
00:09:00,583 --> 00:09:03,125
Commander La Forge? You?

158
00:09:03,125 --> 00:09:05,917
I don't think so.
Thanks, anyway.

159
00:09:05,917 --> 00:09:08,792
(<i> chuckles</i> )
I have rarely encountered

160
00:09:08,792 --> 00:09:10,667
such squeamish people.

161
00:09:10,667 --> 00:09:14,000
Dr. Crusher?
Commander Riker?

162
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,959
Mr. Tarmin, are all Ullians
able to read memories?

163
00:09:16,959 --> 00:09:19,083
Oh, no, my dear.

164
00:09:19,083 --> 00:09:21,166
The technique requires
special training.

165
00:09:21,166 --> 00:09:23,417
It is a serious commitment.

166
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:26,083
INAD: It takes
years of study.

167
00:09:26,083 --> 00:09:30,291
Tarmin is the most
proficient of our group.

168
00:09:30,291 --> 00:09:33,583
Once, Jev spent two days

169
00:09:33,583 --> 00:09:35,959
with a contingent
of elderly Gentons.

170
00:09:35,959 --> 00:09:37,667
He couldn't get anything
from them.

171
00:09:37,667 --> 00:09:39,917
I spent only one hour
with them and retrieved

172
00:09:39,917 --> 00:09:42,583
a fragment from the
Gentonian trade wars.

173
00:09:42,583 --> 00:09:44,250
Excuse me.

174
00:09:45,291 --> 00:09:48,083
(<i> door opens, closes</i> )

175
00:09:48,083 --> 00:09:50,417
Exactly how long
will it be

176
00:09:50,417 --> 00:09:52,625
before we get to Kaldra,
Captain?

177
00:09:52,625 --> 00:09:53,959
PICARD:
Mr. Data?

178
00:09:53,959 --> 00:09:56,125
DATA:
Four days, 11 hours.

179
00:10:00,041 --> 00:10:02,709
Jev?

180
00:10:02,709 --> 00:10:05,583
I'm sorry, I--
I'm being rude.

181
00:10:05,583 --> 00:10:07,125
No, not at all.

182
00:10:07,125 --> 00:10:10,208
My father finds it amusing
to demean me in public.

183
00:10:10,208 --> 00:10:13,458
I reach the point where I
don't wanna hear any more.

184
00:10:13,458 --> 00:10:16,250
It's not easy having
an overbearing parent.

185
00:10:16,250 --> 00:10:18,417
Believe me,
I know how you feel.

186
00:10:18,417 --> 00:10:20,333
Oh, that's right--
you're an empath.

187
00:10:20,333 --> 00:10:22,542
Oh, I can't read Ullians.

188
00:10:22,542 --> 00:10:25,458
But I do know a
certain Betazoid mother

189
00:10:25,458 --> 00:10:28,291
who is a great deal
like your father.

190
00:10:30,709 --> 00:10:32,041
Deck eight.

191
00:10:32,041 --> 00:10:33,875
Deck 16.

192
00:10:33,875 --> 00:10:37,041
I've learned to remind myself
that my mother and I

193
00:10:37,041 --> 00:10:39,417
are two separate
individuals.

194
00:10:39,417 --> 00:10:42,166
Mm-hmm... and have you
enjoyed much success

195
00:10:42,166 --> 00:10:44,375
with this approach,
Counselor?

196
00:10:45,917 --> 00:10:50,500
No... but I do keep
reminding myself.

197
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:52,542
(<i> laughs</i> )

198
00:10:52,542 --> 00:10:53,625
Good night.

199
00:10:53,625 --> 00:10:55,291
Good night,
Counselor, and...

200
00:10:55,291 --> 00:10:57,375
and thank you.

201
00:11:24,083 --> 00:11:26,500
RIKER: Have you stopped
thinking about us?

202
00:11:37,250 --> 00:11:39,083
Hot chocolate.

203
00:12:01,333 --> 00:12:02,583
(<i> gasps</i> )

204
00:12:15,875 --> 00:12:18,291
<i>Imzadi,</i> we can't--

205
00:12:18,291 --> 00:12:20,834
not when we're serving
on the same ship.

206
00:12:20,834 --> 00:12:23,000
Have you stopped
thinking about us?

207
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:24,500
Just answer that.

208
00:12:29,709 --> 00:12:32,875
I can't stop
thinking about you.

209
00:12:32,875 --> 00:12:34,333
Will, don't.

210
00:12:34,333 --> 00:12:36,333
Imzadi,<i> we can't--</i>

211
00:12:36,333 --> 00:12:39,250
<i>not when we're serving</i>
<i>on the same ship.</i>

212
00:12:39,250 --> 00:12:42,000
Have you stopped
thinking about us?

213
00:12:49,375 --> 00:12:51,500
We mustn't do this.

214
00:12:51,500 --> 00:12:53,166
Will, don't!

215
00:12:53,166 --> 00:12:55,333
Will...
no!

216
00:12:56,250 --> 00:12:57,959
(<i> gasps</i> )

217
00:13:01,333 --> 00:13:03,375
<i>Imzadi...</i>

218
00:13:03,375 --> 00:13:06,041
RIKER:<i> Have you stopped</i>
<i>thinking about us?</i>

219
00:13:06,041 --> 00:13:08,166
<i>Just answer that.</i>

220
00:13:08,166 --> 00:13:10,291
No! No!

221
00:13:10,291 --> 00:13:12,375
Don't! Don't!

222
00:13:12,375 --> 00:13:15,083
I can't stop
thinking about you.

223
00:13:18,208 --> 00:13:19,667
<i>Imzadi.</i>

224
00:13:20,709 --> 00:13:22,458
Have you stopped
thinking about us?

225
00:13:22,458 --> 00:13:25,500
(<i> echoing</i> )
No!

226
00:13:40,166 --> 00:13:43,417
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 45430.9.</i>

227
00:13:43,417 --> 00:13:46,500
<i>Counselor Troi</i>
<i>has fallen into a deep coma.</i>

228
00:13:46,500 --> 00:13:47,917
<i>After thorough examination,</i>

229
00:13:47,917 --> 00:13:49,709
<i>Dr. Crusher</i>
<i>has been unable to find</i>

230
00:13:49,709 --> 00:13:51,625
<i>signs of illness or infection.</i>

231
00:13:51,625 --> 00:13:53,417
Any change,
Dr. Martin?

232
00:13:53,417 --> 00:13:56,709
No, I'm still getting unusual
neural transmitter readings

233
00:13:56,709 --> 00:13:58,500
in the diencephalon.

234
00:13:58,500 --> 00:14:01,125
But they might be a
result of the coma.

235
00:14:01,125 --> 00:14:02,875
Can you bring her
out of it?

236
00:14:02,875 --> 00:14:04,875
I've tried standard
revival techniques.

237
00:14:04,875 --> 00:14:06,333
She doesn't respond.

238
00:14:06,333 --> 00:14:07,875
Until I find out
what's caused this,

239
00:14:07,875 --> 00:14:09,792
I don't want to try anything
more extreme.

240
00:14:09,792 --> 00:14:11,709
Do you know what she was
doing when this happened?

241
00:14:11,709 --> 00:14:14,250
No. She was found in
her quarters this morning

242
00:14:14,250 --> 00:14:16,041
when she didn't show up
for an appointment.

243
00:14:16,041 --> 00:14:18,542
She was dressed for bed, but
the bed hadn't been slept in.

244
00:14:18,542 --> 00:14:20,875
Who was the last person
to speak with her?

245
00:14:20,875 --> 00:14:23,125
She left the dinner last night
with one of the Ullians.

246
00:14:23,125 --> 00:14:24,458
I'll talk to him.

247
00:14:25,709 --> 00:14:27,500
Ask if they would consent

248
00:14:27,500 --> 00:14:29,667
to an examination,
just to be certain.

249
00:14:29,667 --> 00:14:31,375
Mmm.

250
00:14:31,375 --> 00:14:32,875
I'll check
the bio-filter readings

251
00:14:32,875 --> 00:14:34,750
from the Ullian transporter log.

252
00:14:34,750 --> 00:14:37,417
It's possible they could still
be carrying a harmful organism.

253
00:14:59,542 --> 00:15:00,959
May I join you?

254
00:15:00,959 --> 00:15:03,041
Commander...
of course.

255
00:15:03,041 --> 00:15:04,583
Something's wrong?

256
00:15:04,583 --> 00:15:06,125
Counselor Troi is ill.

257
00:15:06,125 --> 00:15:07,542
I'm sorry to hear it.

258
00:15:07,542 --> 00:15:09,542
She's more than ill,
she's in a coma.

259
00:15:09,542 --> 00:15:11,458
Dr. Crusher doesn't
know what's causing it

260
00:15:11,458 --> 00:15:12,792
or how to treat her.

261
00:15:12,792 --> 00:15:14,125
When did this happen?

262
00:15:14,125 --> 00:15:16,250
Apparently
sometime last night.

263
00:15:16,250 --> 00:15:17,875
That's why I wanted
to talk to you.

264
00:15:17,875 --> 00:15:21,500
You may have been the
last person to see her.

265
00:15:21,500 --> 00:15:23,625
Did you go with her
into her quarters?

266
00:15:25,250 --> 00:15:28,625
Are you suggesting that I
behaved improperly, Commander?

267
00:15:29,667 --> 00:15:30,917
Not at all.

268
00:15:30,917 --> 00:15:32,625
I'm just trying
to trace her steps.

269
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:37,458
We talked...
in a turbolift briefly.

270
00:15:37,458 --> 00:15:41,542
She got out at deck eight.
I did not go with her.

271
00:15:41,542 --> 00:15:44,959
Jev, I'm not accusing
you of anything.

272
00:15:44,959 --> 00:15:47,250
Did she mention
feeling ill?

273
00:15:47,250 --> 00:15:49,750
She seemed fine.

274
00:15:49,750 --> 00:15:52,208
She has a wonderful
sense of humor.

275
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:57,625
If you have no objections,

276
00:15:57,625 --> 00:16:00,417
Dr. Crusher would like to
examine you and your group.

277
00:16:00,417 --> 00:16:02,500
To what end?
She's just trying to eliminate

278
00:16:02,500 --> 00:16:05,000
the possibility that one of you
might be a carrying an organism

279
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,542
that was harmful
to Deanna.

280
00:16:07,542 --> 00:16:10,458
I'm not implying that you
did anything intentional.

281
00:16:10,458 --> 00:16:12,959
I'm just trying to get to
the bottom of the mystery.

282
00:16:14,125 --> 00:16:15,583
We have nothing to hide.

283
00:16:15,583 --> 00:16:17,333
If you wish to spend
time examining us--

284
00:16:17,333 --> 00:16:19,083
Fine, thank you.

285
00:16:38,458 --> 00:16:40,208
Deanna...

286
00:16:41,458 --> 00:16:43,041
I don't know if
you can hear me.

287
00:16:43,041 --> 00:16:45,000
I've-- I've heard doctors say

288
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:47,792
that even when someone's
in a coma,

289
00:16:47,792 --> 00:16:51,750
they may be able to hear
when people talk to them...

290
00:16:51,750 --> 00:16:57,333
that it might help stimulate
the brain, speed healing.

291
00:16:57,333 --> 00:17:00,291
In fact, I think you
did that for me once,

292
00:17:00,291 --> 00:17:03,166
when I was in pretty bad shape.

293
00:17:05,834 --> 00:17:08,166
I just thought...

294
00:17:10,166 --> 00:17:13,625
it might help to
hear a friendly voice...

295
00:17:13,625 --> 00:17:17,000
even if you don't know
you're hearing it.

296
00:17:18,458 --> 00:17:21,125
We've been busy
mapping the sector.

297
00:17:21,125 --> 00:17:24,041
It's been pretty routine.

298
00:17:24,041 --> 00:17:28,291
The most unusual thing we've
seen is a binary star system.

299
00:17:28,291 --> 00:17:30,792
Let's see,
what else?

300
00:17:30,792 --> 00:17:34,583
I've finished the personnel
review that we were working on.

301
00:17:36,625 --> 00:17:39,458
You can check it out...

302
00:17:39,458 --> 00:17:41,709
when you wake up.

303
00:17:47,792 --> 00:17:49,792
I miss you.

304
00:17:49,792 --> 00:17:52,875
Please, don't stay away
too long.

305
00:17:55,875 --> 00:17:57,709
Will...

306
00:18:00,166 --> 00:18:01,917
Will, I promise
I'll let you know

307
00:18:01,917 --> 00:18:05,542
the minute she regains
consciousness.

308
00:18:05,542 --> 00:18:07,041
I know.

309
00:18:07,041 --> 00:18:08,834
There's nothing
you can do here.

310
00:18:08,834 --> 00:18:11,333
You'll wear
yourself out.

311
00:18:11,333 --> 00:18:12,875
All right.

312
00:18:12,875 --> 00:18:15,917
It's late.
Go to bed.

313
00:18:17,458 --> 00:18:19,375
